 {"id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.2","title":"B.2: Implement interactive chart drill-down from analytics to filtered search","description":"WHAT: When viewing analytics charts (bar charts, heatmap cells, line chart points), allow the user to press Enter on a selected data element to drill down into filtered search results for that dimension. For example: clicking a bar in the top-agents chart filters search to that agent; clicking a heatmap cell filters to that date; clicking a line chart point shows sessions from that time period. WHY: Analytics without drill-down is a dead end. Users see interesting patterns (spike in token usage, unexpected agent activity) but cannot investigate further without manually typing filters. Drill-down creates the analytics-to-search flow that makes the TUI genuinely useful for investigation. HOW: (1) Add selection state to chart views (selected_bar_idx, selected_cell, etc.), (2) handle Enter in analytics views to construct a filter (agent, workspace, date range), (3) dispatch CassMsg that applies the filter and switches to search view, (4) show breadcrumb indicating drill-down origin. Heatmap cells map to date ranges, bar chart bars map to dimension values, line chart points map to time buckets. KEY FILES: src/ui/analytics_charts.rs (chart rendering), src/ui/app.rs (analytics key handling at lines 8114-8232, filter state). ACCEPTANCE: Enter on any chart element drills down to appropriately filtered search results, with breadcrumb showing drill-down context.","status":"closed","priority":0,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T05:58:56.062653217Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T20:15:54.785502181Z","closed_at":"2026-02-13T20:15:54.785408086Z","close_reason":"Completed: analytics drilldown now applies workspace/source dimension filters; added context + override tests; validated via check/clippy/fmt and analytics_drilldown test suite.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.2","depends_on_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T05:58:56.062653217Z","created_by":"ubuntu"},{"issue_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.2","depends_on_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T06:01:29.601179538Z","created_by":"ubuntu"}]}
 {"id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.3","title":"B.3: Add hourly-granularity timeline view to analytics Explorer","description":"WHAT: The analytics Explorer currently defaults to daily/weekly/monthly time buckets. Add hourly granularity option, rendering a dense timeline that shows intraday patterns (when are agents most active, token usage spikes, cost patterns within a day). WHY: The hourly rollup data exists in usage_hourly table but is not surfaced in the TUI. Hourly patterns reveal important information: overnight agent runs, peak usage hours, cost optimization opportunities. This was listed as a gap in the analytics audit — stored but not surfaced. HOW: (1) Add GroupBy::Hour option to the Explorer metric selector, (2) query usage_hourly table when hourly granularity selected, (3) render with LineChart using denser x-axis (24 ticks per day vs 1), (4) add date range selector since hourly data for long periods is too dense — default to last 7 days when hourly selected. KEY FILES: src/ui/analytics_charts.rs (render_explorer), src/analytics/query.rs (query_tokens_timeseries with GroupBy), src/analytics/types.rs (GroupBy enum, already has Hour variant). ACCEPTANCE: Explorer view shows hourly granularity option, renders clean timeline for last 7 days, auto-switches to daily for longer ranges.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T05:58:56.725181366Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T20:12:12.355184612Z","close_reason":"Completed: Hourly Explorer now defaults to 7d and auto-falls back to Daily for long zoom ranges; tests and quality gates passed","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.3","depends_on_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T05:58:56.725181366Z","created_by":"ubuntu"},{"issue_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.3","depends_on_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T06:01:29.673513670Z","created_by":"ubuntu"}]}
 {"id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.4","title":"B.4: Add canvas-rendered scatter plots and area fills to analytics charts","description":"WHAT: Use ftui_extras::canvas Painter API to add: (1) scatter plot in Explorer showing token count vs message count per session (reveals efficiency patterns), (2) area fill under line charts for visual weight, (3) annotations on charts (labels for peaks, averages, trends). WHY: The current charts are bar/line/sparkline only. Scatter plots reveal correlations that bar charts cannot (e.g. which agents produce more tokens per message). Area fills make line charts more readable. Annotations provide context without requiring the user to mentally calculate. The Canvas feature is already compiled in but only used for the heatmap. HOW: (1) Use ftui_extras::canvas::Painter to draw scatter points (small filled circles at data coordinates), (2) add area fill by drawing filled polygons under line series, (3) implement annotation labels using canvas text rendering. Data for scatter plots: query per-session token counts and message counts from analytics. KEY FILES: src/ui/analytics_charts.rs (Canvas import already present at line 15), src/analytics/query.rs (breakdown queries provide per-session data). ACCEPTANCE: Explorer view has scatter plot option, line charts have optional area fill, peak values are annotated.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T05:58:57.098561140Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T20:12:12.428832350Z","close_reason":"Completed: Explorer canvas scatter + line area fill + peak/avg/trend annotations","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.4","depends_on_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T05:58:57.098561140Z","created_by":"ubuntu"},{"issue_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.4","depends_on_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3nwtd.2.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T06:01:29.745883609Z","created_by":"ubuntu"}]}

